# 5. Silver Layer

The Silver layer performs **data cleaning and feature engineering**.

This stage transforms raw event data into structured datasets suitable for analytics and machine learning.

---

## 5.1 Data Cleaning

Cleaning transformations include:

- timestamp normalization
- event type standardization
- duplicate removal
- schema validation

These steps ensure that downstream pipelines operate on **consistent and reliable data**.

---

## 5.2 Sessionization

User activity is grouped into sessions using a **30-minute inactivity threshold**.

If the time between two events exceeds 30 minutes, a new session is created.
User Events
↓
Time Gap Detection
↓
Session Boundary Creation

Sessionization enables the computation of behavioral metrics such as:

- session activity
- session purchase behavior
- browsing intensity

---

## 5.3 Behavioral Feature Engineering

Behavioral features summarize user interaction patterns within sessions.

Examples include:

| Feature | Description |
|-------|-------------|
| total_events | number of actions in session |
| views | number of product views |
| add_to_cart | number of cart additions |
| purchases | number of purchases |
| avg_price | average price of viewed products |

These features represent **user engagement signals**.

---

## 5.4 Product Popularity Features

Product demand is measured using time-window aggregations.

Example feature:

| Feature | Description |
|-------|-------------|
| events_last_hour | number of interactions per product in last hour |

These signals capture **trending products**, which are commonly used in recommendation systems.

---

## 5.5 Customer Value Features (RFM)

Customer value is modeled using the **Recency-Frequency-Monetary framework**.

| Feature | Description |
|-------|-------------|
| recency_days | days since last interaction |
| frequency | number of user events |
| monetary_value | total purchase value |

RFM features are widely used in:

- customer segmentation
- marketing targeting
- purchase prediction models

